args: ＂Ah ha ha ha! Foolish princess!\nI'll never allow ya to marry the prince!＂
＂His lawful wedded wife shall be me,\nthe witch! Now seize her, yeah?!＂
＂N-no, I will never allow you to...＂
Oh, but this is foolishness itself.\nWhat are we even DOING?
YOU were the one who said you always\nwanted the princess role whenever\nyour orphanage put on a play!
We're just trying to help you do that.\nYou weren't just making all that up,\nwere you?
Heaven forbid! Lies are this world's\nmost abominable of evils!
However, I merely wanted to TELL you\nof this memory—not to have you attempt\nto rectify it in the present day.

Look, you're dressed all princess-like,
and I spent at least ten minutes tryin'
to memorize these lines, so we might
as well do this thing, yeah?
Ranzal is correct about your dress;\nit truly does make you look like royalty.
I quite agree. Incidentally, now that we've\nall broken character, what roles DID you\nused to play when you were a child?
I assume the fact you always wanted to\nbe cast as the princess means you were\nusually given other roles instead?
Uh oh. Is it that bad? Were ya like\nSad Mute Villager or somethin'?\nOr didja have to play Big Bad Fiend?
Still, I never pictured you\nwanting to be a princess.
I'm well aware the role does not suit me.
Oh, that's not what I'm saying at all.\nI just think it's kind of cute.
Pray do not tease me about this;\nI had a very serious reason for\nwanting to play such a part.
Someone always comes to the rescue\nof a princess in the end.
I have always been...intensely jealous\nof this fact.
Oh, man. You wanted to be a princess\nbecause it meant your parents might\ncome back for you?
No, seriously, there ain't no reason to be\nso down about this—ya got a chance to\nmake yer childhood dream come true!
Yeah! Just have fun being a princess!
Hey, why don't we just skip to the scene\nwhere a prince comes to rescue you?
And who is playing this prince?
Hee hee! Well, if you want a serious\nmethod actor, he's your man!
Okay, so we're gonna do the scene after\nthe evil witch is defeated, which is the\nclimactic kiss! Let's gooo!
I don't remember there being a\nkissing scene in this play.
Eh, I figured it'd be more exciting this way,\nso I threw one in.
You probably should have run that\ndecision past the rest of us first.
It doesn't have to be a REAL kiss!\nJust get real close and act like it\nor whatever.
Now places, everyone! And remember,\nthis is all for Hildegarde!
＂I have come for you, Princess. I was so\nworried when I heard that you had been\ncaptured, I thought my heart would break.＂
(A-are we really going to do a\nkiss scene?!)
＂But the pain I endured made me realize\nthat what I feel for you is true love.＂
(W-well, I'm older than him, I should be\nable to handle this...)
(Everyone is pouring their heart and soul\ninto this play, and it's all for me.)
(I can't make all of their effort for nothing.\nB-but a kiss?!)
＂I'm so glad that you feel the same way.\nThen let us kiss, that our feelings for\none another may never change.＂
Yeah, I think she just grazed me.
Okay, what is this, Improv 101?\nThe script clearly does NOT tell you\nto knock the prince out!
I'm sorry, but I simply cannot do something\nso obscene as a public display of affection.
And even if you weren't all watching me,\nthe goddess would be!
Such lewd behavior would not\nplease her in the slightest.
I see acting in a play only goes so far\ntoward changing a person's nature.
I cannot and shall not lie to the goddess.\nYou all have my heartfelt apologies.
I think we're going to have to come up\nwith a plan B here, everyone.
Heck, ＂plan B＂ is my middle name!\nWhat else you want, Hildegarde?
I can only think of a single wish\nI have truly ever wanted...
Yes. I want to find my parents.\nOh, but I am a pathetic fool\nto continue to cling to this!

Still, I have always yearned for them to
come and see me perform. Every time I
took the stage, I would search for their
faces in the audience.
Hoping your parents will show up for\na play seems like a VERY roundabout\nway to find them.
Why don't we just go look for them?
Oh, this is all naive foolishness.\nWhat interest would they possibly have\nin seeing me after all this time?!
If you're always afraid of the first step,\nyou'll never take a journey.
There are some wishes that prayer alone\ncan't grant, remember? And just hoping\nfor it won't get the job done either.
So let's go out there and make your dream\ncome true—together.
Your guiding voice has reached me more\nplainly than any oracle.
Yes. Thanks to you, I feel I can finally\nleave my weakness in the past.
Will you help me find my parents?
You've dreamed of this long enough;\nlet's go make it come true.
